{"Body": "<strong>Emily Flaherty</strong> | Contributing Writer\r\n\r\nToday, CRANN and the Trinity Centre for Bioengineering (TCBE), together\u00a0with University College Cork (UCC) and the Royal College of Surgeons (RCSI) are launching AMBER, a\u00a0new Science Foundation Ireland (SFI) research centre.\r\n\r\n&euro;50 million has been invested into AMBER (which stands for Advanced Materials and Bio-Engineering Research Centre)\u00a0by the educational institutions, and also by 18 industry\u00a0partners. It has been set up to advance and further develop new materials and medical devices in\u00a0the ICT, medical device and industrial technology sectors, for which it will have the help of leading\u00a0scientific and industry researchers in Physics, Chemistry, Bioengineering and Medicine, and the\u00a0support of international companies and collaborators.\r\n\r\nAMBER was launched by Minister of State Sean Sherlock in Croke Park this morning. Professor\u00a0Mark Ferguson, Director General of SFI and various representatives from the educational institutions\u00a0and industrial partners are also speaking at the event. This will be followed by a poster session and some\u00a0short presentations on CRANN research in the afternoon. The launch will conclude with a gala\u00a0dinner. The event, which began at 10am, will continue until late in the Hogan Suite on the 5th\u00a0floor of the Croke\u00a0Park Conference Centre.", "Imageurl": "http://universitytimes.ie/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/bioengineering.png", "Thumb_nail": "http://universitytimes.ie/wp-content/uploads/2013/utlogo.jpg", "ID": "20806", "Heading": "Trinity Centre for Bioengineering Launches &euro;50m Research Centre"}